notes.text: The word media comes from the Latin plural of medium. The traditional view is that it should therefore be treated as a plural noun in all its senses in English and be used with a plural rather than a singular verb: the media have not followed the reports (rather than ‘has’). In practice, in the sense ‘television, radio, and the press collectively’, it behaves as a collective noun (like staff or clergy, for example), which means that it is now acceptable in standard English for it to take either a singular or a plural verb. The word is also increasingly used in the plural form medias, as if it had a conventional singular form media, especially when referring to different forms of new media, and in the sense ‘the material or form used by an artist’: there were great efforts made by the medias of the involved countries about 600 works in all genres and medias were submitted for review.

definitions: any of a number of trees that have wood or foliage similar to the box tree.

notes.text: several Australian eucalyptus trees (genus Eucalyptus, family Myrtaceae).
the tropical American Venezuelan box or West Indian box (Casearia praecox, family Flacourtiaceae), the timber of which has now largely replaced that of the European box.

etymologies: mid 18th century: perhaps from Spanish bojar ‘sail round’, from Middle Low German bōgen ‘bend’, from the base of bow
late Middle English: from Old French joe ‘cheek, jaw’, of unknown origin

definitions: each of the upper and lower bony structures in vertebrates forming the framework of the mouth and containing the teeth.
shortDefinitions: bony structure in mouth containing teeth

definitions: the lower movable bone of the jaw, or the part of the face containing it

examples.text: she suffered a broken jaw

shortDefinitions: lower movable bone of this structure

definitions: the mouth with its bones and teeth.
the grasping, biting, or crushing mouthparts of an invertebrate.
the gripping parts of a tool or machine, such as a wrench or vice.
shortDefinitions: gripping parts of tool or machine

definitions: the grasping or destructive power of something

examples.text: victory was snatched from the jaws of defeat

definitions: an opening likened to a mouth

examples.text: a passenger stepping from the jaws of a car ferry

definitions: talk or gossip, especially when lengthy or tedious

examples.text: committee work is just endless jaw

definitions: talk at length; chatter

examples.text: I was too busy to spend time jawing with the rest of the crew
